ffort to respond to national goals and requirements. Its traditional law, the Shari'ah, is the fundamental law of all Islamic societies, and Debs's analysis of Egypt's experience demonstrates how Islamic jurisprudence can be sophisticated, coherent, rational, and effective, developed over centuries to serve the needs of societies that flourished under the rule of law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aProperty (Islamic law) 0aProperty (Islamic law)zEgypt. 0aPropertyzEgypt. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aAl-Sayyid, Ridwan.1 aAl-sayyid, Ridwan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDebs, Richard A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVogel, Frank E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVogel, Frank.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/debs1504440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231520997423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231520997/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK